Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Approximately 17 000 Cambodians are said to have been treated with multidrug therapy (MDT) and cured of leprosy in the last 15 years [1] and Cambodia achieved the goal of "elimination" of leprosy as a public health problem in 1998, with a prevalence of less than 1 case per 10 000 people. The number of new cases detected (incidence rate per 100 000) was 747 (6.2) in 2000 [2], 740 (5.8) in 2002 [3], 509 (3.9) in 2003 [4], 461 (3.5) in 2004 [1], 429 (3.1) in 2005 [5], and continued to fall each year until 262 cases (1.8) in 2010 [4]. The article above implies that this fall in numbers of new cases reported annually from 2003 to 2010 may have been due to inadequate case finding as a result of insufficient resources.

The number of new cases (incidence rate per 100 000) then rose in 2011 to 475 (3.2) in 2012 [6]. The almost 500 registered new cases of leprosy in Cambodia in 2012 is still less than a third of the number of new cases reported annually 2 decades ago [7].

